  "prompt": "What's a graph comparison for X=2 and y=x+2?",
  "response": "To compare the graph of \\( y = x + 2 \\) with \\( x = 2 \\), you need to understand both equations:\n\n1. **Graph of \\( y = x + 2 \\)**: This is a linear equation. It has a y-intercept of 2 (meaning it crosses the y-axis at (0, 2)) and a slope of 1 (which means for every unit increase in \\( x \\), \\( y \\) increases by the same amount). The line will extend infinitely in both directions.\n\n2. **Graph of \\( x = 2 \\)**: This represents a vertical line where the x-coordinate is always 2. This line extends infinitely in the positive and negative y-directions at \\( x = 2 \\).\n\n### Graph Comparison\n- For \\( y = x + 2 \\):\n  - When \\( x = 2 \\), \\( y = 2 + 2 = 4 \\). So the point (2, 4) lies on the line.\n  \n- For \\( x = 2 \\):\n  - This is a vertical line that intersects all values of \\( y \\) at \\( x = 2 \\).\n\n### Intersection Point\nThe lines intersect at the point \\( (2, 4) \\). At this point, the line \\( y = x + 2 \\) meets the vertical line \\( x = 2 \\).\n\n### Visualization\n- The graph of \\( y = x + 2 \\) is a straight line going upward from left to right, while \\( x = 2 \\) is a vertical line. Visualizing or plotting both on a coordinate plane will show you how they intersect at the point (2, 4).",
